    base:desc "The DT lifecycle follows the MBSE multi‑level abstraction model described in Section II.B.1. Initial requirements are captured in the requirement layer using SysML requirement diagrams. Functional behaviour is expressed in the functional architecture layer through SysML activity and sequence diagrams, potentially enriched by MontiArc automaton or SysML state machines. The logical architecture is then articulated with ADLs (ACME, AADL, MontiArc) which provide component‑connector views and detailed interface definitions. Finally, at the product/technical layer the DT is instantiated as executable code – typically generated from SysML or MontiArc models and implemented in C++ or Java – and integrated with simulation environments such as MathWorks Simulink for dynamic validation. Transition between stages is managed by traceability links inherent in the MBSE toolchain (e.g., SysML requirement to function, to component, to code). Governance of the lifecycle relies on MBSE best practices, including version control of models, change management, and model‑to‑code consistency checks. This staged, traceable approach ensures that each abstraction level receives a dedicated representation, and that evolution from conception to deployment is orchestrated through rigorous documentation and tool support."
]

